Package org.opensextant.geodesy

Class Geodetic2DBounds

java.lang.Object
org.opensextant.geodesy.Geodetic2DBounds
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable
Direct Known Subclasses:
Geodetic3DBounds, UnmodifiableGeodetic2DBounds
public class Geodetic2DBounds extends Object implements Serializable
The Geodetic2DBounds class is used to store min and max values for a pair of Geodetic2DPoint coordinates. Since the range of longitudes may cross the international date line, coordinates are identified by their compass directions. The signed value of the west-most longitude may therefore be greater than the signed value of the east-most longitude. A bounding box may be degenerate if it is only defined by a single point, and it may be grown around a set of points by successive calls to the include method.

    • Geodetic2DBounds

    • Geodetic2DBounds

      public Geodetic2DBounds(Geodetic2DPoint westCoordinate, Geodetic2DPoint eastCoordinate)
      This constructor will accept west and east Geodetic2DPoint coordinates and set the bounding box limits accordingly. Note that the source coordinate components are used by reference (i.e. they are not cloned). The first coordinate is used to set the west Longitude even if its value is greater than the east, so boxes that span the international date line can be accommodated by this convention of listing lons in reverse order. On the other hand, latitude values are normalized so that south is always less than north.
      Parameters:
      westCoordinate - western most point
      eastCoordinate - eastern most point
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if westCoordinate or eastCoordinate is null

    • Geodetic2DBounds

      Parameters:

      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if seedPoint is null

      Throws:

    • Geodetic2DBounds

      public Geodetic2DBounds(Geodetic2DPoint center, double radius, int nPoints)
      This constructor takes a geodetic center point and radius in meters, and constructs a new Geodetic2DBounds bounding box that inscribes (contains) the specified circle, constructed by iterating around the boundary of the circle at the specified number of points of resolution.
      Parameters:
      center - Geodetic2DPoint at the center of the inscribed circle
      radius - double radius (in meters) of the inscribed circle
      nPoints - number of points to include from circle boundary. Using n=4 generates the north, south, east, and west corner points which is essentially the maximal boundary for a circle and the same if nPoints=8, 32, or 64 points unless the center point is at/near the poles in which circle bounds are irregular. Value should be greater than 0 and typically is 4. If value is 1 then a line segment is drawn from the center to the southern edge. Value = 2 draws a line segment from north to south edges.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if center is nulls
      ArithmeticException - if nPoints = 0

    • Geodetic2DBounds

    • Geodetic2DBounds

      public Geodetic2DBounds(Geodetic2DEllipse ellipse, int count)
      Ctor to create a bounding box around an ellipse. The method used is to divide the ellipse into n points and calculate the min and max lat and lon values for the ellipse. It is recommended that a count should be used that is divisible by 4 in order to ensure that 4 of the points will land along the two axis of the ellipse.
      Parameters:
      ellipse - the ellipse, never null
      count - the number of slices to divide the ellipse up into when finding the min and max points of the ellipse.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if ellipse is null

  • Method Details

    • include

      public void include(Geodetic2DPoint newPoint)
      This method is used to extend this bounding box to include a new point. If the new point is already inside the existing bounding box, no change will result. The bounding box is always extended by the smallest amount necessary to include the new point. Sometimes this will cause the bounding box to wrap around the international date line.
      Parameters:
      newPoint - new Geodetic2DPoint point to include in bounding box.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if newPoint is null

    • include

      public void include(Geodetic2DBounds bbox)
      This method is used to extend this bounding box to include another bounding box. If the newly specified bounding box is inside the existing bounding box, no change will result. This bounding box is always extended by the smallest amount necessary to include the new bounding box. Sometimes this will cause this bounding box to wrap around the international date line.
      Parameters:
      bbox - additional Geodetic2DBounds to include in this one.
      Throws:
      NullPointerException - if bbox is null
